Recursive and adaptive estimation:

  • Introduction to Chapter 11
  • Recursive LS, Section 11.1

Why recursive and adaptive estimation?

  • As time passes we get more information
  • Models are approximations
  • The best approximation change over time
  • Makes it possible to produce software which learns as new data becomes available

Types of models considered

REG:

\(Y_t = Âµ + Î²_1U_{1,t} + Î²_2U_{2,t} + \ldots + Î²_mU_{m,t} + Îµ_t\)

\[ \begin{aligned} Ï(B)Y_t &= Âµ + Ï(B)U_t + Îµ_t â \\ Y_t &= Âµ â Ï_1Y_{tâ1} â \ldots â Ï_pY_{tâp}\\ &+ Ï_0U_t + \ldots + Ï_sU_{tâs} + Îµ_t \end{aligned} \]

LS-estimate at time t

Model:

\[ Y_t = x^T_t Î¸ + Îµ_t \]

Data (x may contain lagged values of the ârealâ input):

\[ Y_1, Y_2, Y_3, Y_4, \ldots , Y_{tâ1}, Y_t\\ x_1,x_2,x_3,x_4, \ldots ,x_{tâ1},x_t \]

LS-estimate based on t observations:

\[ \begin{aligned} \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t &= \operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\widehat{\theta}} S_t(\mathbf Î¸) = (\mathbf X^T\mathbf X)^{â1}\mathbf X^T\mathbf Y\\ S_t(\mathbf Î¸) &= \sum^t_{s=1} (Y_s â \mathbf x^T_s \mathbf Î¸)^2 \end{aligned} \]

From one time step to the next (in an easy way)

The trick is to realize that:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf R_t &= \mathbf X^T\mathbf X = \mathbf x_1\mathbf x^T_1 + \mathbf x_2\mathbf x^T_2 + \ldots + \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t = \sum^t_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf x^T_s\\ \mathbf h_t &= \mathbf X^T\mathbf Y = \mathbf x_1\mathbf Y_1 + \mathbf x_2\mathbf Y_2 + \ldots + \mathbf x_t\mathbf Y_t = \sum^t_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf Y_s \end{aligned} \]

Where:

\[ \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t = \left[\begin{array}{cccc} x_{1,t}x_{1,t} & x_{1,t}x_{2,t} & \cdots & x_{1,t}x_{p,t}\\ x_{2,t}x_{1,t} & x_{2,t}x_{2,t} & \cdots & x_{2,t}x_{p,t}\\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ x_{p,t}x_{1,t} & x_{p,t}x_{2,t} & \cdots & x_{p,t}x_{p,t} \end{array}\right] \quad \mathbf x_t\mathbf Y_t = \left[\begin{array}{c} x_{1,t}Y_t\\ x_{2,t}Y_t\\ \vdots\\ x_{p,t}Y_t \end{array}\right] \]

Then:

\[ \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t = \mathbf R^{â1}_t\mathbf h_t\\ \mathbf R_t = \sum^t_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf x^T_s = \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t + \sum^{tâ1}_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf x^T_s = \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t + \mathbf R_{tâ1}\\ \mathbf h_t = \sum^t_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf Y_s = \mathbf x_t\mathbf Y_t + \sum^{tâ1}_{s=1} \mathbf x_s\mathbf Y_s = \mathbf x_t\mathbf Y_t + \mathbf h_{tâ1} \]

Initialization:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf R_0 &= \mathbf 0\text{ (matrix of zeros)}\\ \mathbf h_0 &= \mathbf 0\text{ (vector of zeros)}\\ \end{aligned} \]

First estimate of \(\widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t\) when \(\mathbf R_t\) becomes invertible

Other formulations

Eliminating \(\mathbf h_t\):

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf R_t = \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t + \mathbf R_{tâ1}\\ \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t = \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1} + \mathbf R^{â1}_t \mathbf x_t\left(Y_t â \mathbf x^T_t\widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1}\right) \end{aligned} \]

Eliminating \(\mathbf h_t\) and avoiding matrix-inversion:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf K_t &= \frac{\mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t}{1 + \mathbf x^T_t \mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t}\\ \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t &= \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1} + \mathbf K_t\left(Yt â \mathbf x^T_t \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1}\right)\\ \mathbf P_t &= \mathbf P_{tâ1} â \frac{\mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t\mathbf P_{tâ1}}{1 + \mathbf x^T_t \mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t} \end{aligned} \]

Example - Heat consumption revisited

Forgetting old observations

So far we have a way of updating the estimates as the data set grows

If we want a method which forgets old observations we apply weights which start at 1 and goes to 0 when observations gets old

\[ \begin{aligned} \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t &= \operatorname*{arg\,min}_{\widehat{\theta}} S_t(\mathbf Î¸) = (\mathbf X^T\mathbf{WX})^{â1}\mathbf X^T\mathbf{WY}\\ S_t(\mathbf Î¸) &= \sum^t_{s=1} Î²(t, s)(Y_s â \mathbf x^T_s \mathbf Î¸)^2 \end{aligned} \]

where \(\mathbf W = diag(Î²(t, 1), Î²(t, 2), \ldots , Î²(t, t â 1), 1)\)

\(Î²(t, s)\) expresses how we assign weights to old observations

Exponential decay of weights

  • Letâs first consider \(Î²(t, s) = Î»^{tâs} (0 < Î» â¤ 1)\)
    • \(Î» = 1\): What we did with the previous algorithms
    • \(Î» < 1\): We forget in an exponential manner
  • In the general case it turns out that the estimates can be updated recursively if the sequence of weights can be written as
    • \(Î²(t, s) = Î»(t)Î²(t â 1, s),\quad 1 â¤ s â¤ t â 1\)
    • \(Î²(t, t) = 1\)

The Adaptive Recursive LS algorithm

\[ \mathbf R_t = \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t + \color{red}{\lambda(t)}\mathbf R_{tâ1}\\ \mathbf h_t = \mathbf x_t\mathbf Y_t + \color{red}{\lambda(t)}\mathbf h_{tâ1} \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t = \mathbf R^{â1}_t\mathbf h_t\\ \]

Other formulations

Eliminating \(\mathbf h_t\):

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf R_t = \mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t + \color{red}{\lambda(t)}\mathbf R_{tâ1}\\ \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t = \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1} + \mathbf R^{â1}_t \mathbf x_t\left(Y_t â \mathbf x^T_t\widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1}\right) \end{aligned} \]

Eliminating \(\mathbf h_t\) and avoiding matrix-inversion:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathbf K_t &= \frac{\mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t}{\color{red}{\lambda(t)} + \mathbf x^T_t \mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t}\\ \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_t &= \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1} + \mathbf K_t\left(Yt â \mathbf x^T_t \widehat{\mathbf Î¸}_{tâ1}\right)\\ \mathbf P_t &= \mathbf P_{tâ1} â \color{red}{\frac{1}{\lambda(t)}}\left(\frac{\mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t\mathbf x^T_t\mathbf P_{tâ1}}{\color{red}{\lambda(t)} + \mathbf x^T_t \mathbf P_{tâ1}\mathbf x_t}\right) \end{aligned} \]

Constant forgetting

If \(Î»(t) = Î»\) we call \(Î»\) the forgetting factor and define the memory as

\[ T_0 = \sum^{â}_{i=0}Î»^i = 1 + Î» + Î»^2 + Î»^3 + Î»^4 + . . . = \frac{1}{1 â Î»} \]

Given a data set an optimal value of \(Î»\) can be found by âtrial and errorâ

It is often a good idea to select the values of \(Î»\) to be investigated so that the corresponding values of \(T_0\) are approximately equidistant

The criteria to evaluate may depend on the application, but the sum of squared one-step prediction errors is often appropriate

The initialization period should be excluded from the evaluation
